    faqJson: [{ question: "Why does beta thal major present at 6 months?", answer: "At birth, HbF (α2γ2) predominates and is unaffected by beta gene mutations. As the normal fetal-to-adult hemoglobin switch occurs around 6 months, HbF declines and HbA (α2β2) should increase. In beta thal major, beta chains cannot be produced, so HbA fails to increase, and severe anemia develops." }, { question: "What is Hb Bart's?", answer: "Hb Bart's (γ4) consists of four gamma chains. It forms when NO alpha chains are produced (--/-- genotype, all 4 alpha genes deleted). Hb Bart's has extremely high oxygen affinity and cannot deliver oxygen to tissues, causing hydrops fetalis (fatal in utero or shortly after birth)." }]
