    faqJson: [{ question: "How does newborn screening identify sickle cell?", answer: "Newborn screening uses HPLC or isoelectric focusing (IEF) to separate hemoglobins. At birth, HbF predominates. Sickle cell disease: FS pattern (HbF + HbS, no HbA). Sickle trait: FAS (HbF + HbA + HbS, with A > S). Normal: FA (HbF + HbA). HbSC: FSC. All abnormal results require confirmatory testing." }, { question: "Why do sickle cells cause vaso-occlusion?", answer: "Under low O2 conditions, HbS polymerizes into rigid fibers that distort the RBC into a sickle shape. These rigid cells cannot deform through small capillaries, adhere to vascular endothelium (increased expression of adhesion molecules), and obstruct blood flow. This leads to tissue ischemia, pain, and organ damage." }]
